These observations have inspired us to search for new anthracyclines with superior pharmacological properties. Our previous investigations of the tirandamycins7−11 and anthracycline antibiotic cytorhodins12 revealed that both could be readily isolated from Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666 and its mutant strain. ABSTRACT: The C7 (C9 or C10)-O-L-rhodosamine-bearing anthracycline antibiotic cytorhodins and their biosynthetic intermediates were recently isolated from Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666. Cosmid p17C4 from the Streptomyces lydicus genomic library, which harbors both the biosynthetic genes for L-rhodinose (or 2-deoxy-L-fucose) and its glycosyltransferase (encoded by slgG), was introduced into SCSIO 1666 to yield the recombinant strain Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/17C4. investigations of this strain’s secondary metabolic Chemical potential revealed the production of diﬀerent anthracyclines featuring C7-O-L-rhodinose (or 2-deoxy-L-fucose) instead of the typically observed L-rhodosamine. Puriﬁcation of the fermentation broth yielded 12 new anthracycline antibiotics including three new ε-rhodomycinone derivatives, 1, 4, and 8, nine new β-rhodomycinone derivatives, 2, 3, 5−7, and 9−12, and three known compounds, L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose-L- rhodinoserhodomycinone (13), ε-rhodomycinone (14), and γ-rhodomycinone (15). All compounds were characterized on the basis of detailed spectroscopic analyses and comparisons with previously reported data. These compounds exhibited cytotoxicity against a panel of human cancer cell lines. Signiﬁcantly, compounds 4 and 13 displayed pronounced activity against HCT-116 as characterized by IC50 values of 0.3 and 0.2 μM, respectively; these IC50 values are comparable to that of the positive control epirubicin. © XXXX American Chemical Society and American Society of Pharmacognosy Cite This: J. transferases (GTs), CytG1−G3, involved in the sugar transfer processes.12 Cytorhodins are type II PKS-derived metabolites whose synthesis appears to commence with a propionyl-CoA starter unit followed by condensation of nine malonyl-CoA units catalyzed by a minimal polyketide synthase (Ksα, KSβ, and ACP); the C-21 backbone ε-rhodomycinone is the direct result of the PKS machinery. Several sugar tailoring modiﬁcations lead to the mature products. Speciﬁcally, CytG1 is responsible for appending the ﬁrst L-rhodosamine moiety at the C-7 position; CytG2 then transfers the second and third L-rhodinose (or 2- deoxy-L-fucose) moieties to the trisaccharide chain, and CytG3 appears to transfer the L-rhodosamine to both the C-10 and C- 9 positions. It is well documented that the sugar moiety is essential for anthracycline antibiotic’s antitumor activity. Even small to this moiety signiﬁcantly alter cytotoxic modiﬁcations activities and, often, the modes of action for anthracyclines.13 Given this knowledge, we envisioned the application of combinatorial biosynthetic methods to generate glycosylated derivatives with altered pharmacological proﬁles. Here, we describe the introduction of cosmid p17C4 into the strain Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666 en route to the recombinant strain Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/17C4. Importantly, the cosmid p17C4 is derived from the streptolydigin BGC14 from Streptomyces lydicus and contains all the L-rhodinose biosyn- thesis genes as well as the GT encoding gene slgG (Figure 1). the fermentation broth for investigation of Chemical Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/17C4 revealed a diverse metabolite proﬁle relative to the wild-type SCSIO 1666 strain (Figure 2). The newly formed peaks were characterized by UV proﬁles very reminiscent of anthracycline-like metabolites. Fifteen C7-O-L-rhodinose (or 2-deoxy-L-fucose)-bearing an- thracyclines, including three new ε-rhodomycinone derivatives (1, 4, and 8), nine new β-rhodomycinone derivatives (2, 3, 5− 7, and 9−12), and three known compounds (L-rhodinose-L- DOI: 10.1021/acs.jnatprod.8b00212 J. In this paper, we describe hybrid strain construction, structure elucidation, and biological activity evaluations for these compounds. Construction of Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/17C4, Its Fermentation, and Isolation of Metabolites 1−15. For heterologous expression of cosmid p17C4 in Streptomyces sp. SCSIO1666 (Figure 3), the cosmid p17C4 was cloned into the plasmid pSET152AB15 downstream of ermE* to aﬀord p17C4- pSET152AB. The plasmid p17C4-pSET152AB contained all elements necessary for conjugation. Using standard conjugation methods,15 p17C4-pSET152AB was introduced into the heterologous Streptomyces host, and its DNA locus integrated into the chromosome of Streptomyces sp. SCSIO1666. The exconjugator with the correct genotype was designated as Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/17C4. Subsequent 15 L scale fermentation of the mutant strain aﬀorded the crude extract containing all anthracycline congeners of interest. Silica gel chromatography and RP-HPLC puriﬁcation methods aﬀorded analytically pure samples of 1−15. Structure Elucidation. Compound 13 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. HPL Y-11472 with antibacterial activity against Micrococcus luteus with MIC values of <2 μg/ mL.16 The aglycone of compound 13, namely, ε-rhodomyci- none (14), was also isolated as a major component from the crude extract. Another known compound, γ-rhodomycinone (15), was also identiﬁed on the basis of spectroscopic comparisons with previously reported data.12

Compound 1 was obtained as a red, amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C40H50O16 on the basis of HRESIMS. Compound 1 clearly possessed one oxygen atom more than compound 13, thus revealing 1 to have 16 degrees of unsaturation. 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopic data (Table 1), combined with a UV−vis spectrum characteristic of the anthracyclines, conﬁrmed 1 as an anthracycline congener. Further analysis of the 1H NMR data made clear the presence of three adjacent aromatic proton signals (δ H 7.86, 7.69, and 7.30), three H-bonded hydroxy groups (δ H 13.58, 12.76, and 12.12), three anomeric protons (δ H 5.42, d, J = 2.6 Hz; 4.95, d, J = 3.2 Hz; and 4.83, s), and three doublet methyl proton signals (δ H 1.22, 1.21, and 1.18). The 13C NMR spectrum disclosed three carbonyl signals at δ C 190.9, 186.3, and 171.6 along with 12 aromatic carbons in the deshielded sp2-region and 25 aliphatic carbons in the shielded area. Comparisons of the 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopic data with those of 13 revealed that the aglycone moiety and sugar units A and C of 1 were identical to the corresponding moieties of 13, except that the methylene signals at C-3″ (δ C 26.1) in sugar unit B were replaced by an oxygen-bearing methine carbon signal (δ the HMBC correlations from H-1″, H-4″, and 3″-OH to C-3″ conﬁrmed for C-4″ this substitution. The small coupling constants (<3.5 Hz) of three anomeric protons inferred the α-conﬁgurations of these deoxysugar conﬁgura- tions. The connectivity of these deoxysugar moieties was deduced on the basis of HMBC correlations from H-4′ to C-1″ (H-1″ to C-4′) and H-4″ to C-1‴ (H-1⁗ to C-4″); further HMBC correlations of H-1′ to C-7 (H-7 to C-1′) validated the attachment of this trisaccharide chain to the aglycone C-7. Accordingly, a trisaccharide chain consisting of L-rhodinose-2- deoxy-L-fucose-L-rhodinose trisaccharide was subsequently conﬁrmed through full interpretation of COSY and HMBC correlations (Figure 5). Thus, the structure of 1 was established and named L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-L-rhodinose-ε-rhodo- mycinone.

Compound 2 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C38H48O15 on the basis of HRESIMS. The 1H and 13C NMR data acquired for 2 closely resembled those of 1, indicating similar core scaﬀolds. The only diﬀerence between the two compounds was the replacement of the C-10 tethered −COOCH3 in 1 with the hydroxy moiety at the C-10 of compound 2. This methyl ester for OH switch on going from 1 to 2 was further supported by HMBC correlations from H-13 and H-8 to C-10. The singlet sharp peak observed at δ H 4.88 of H-10 also supported this conclusion. Ultimately, full assignment of compound 2 was established using 1D and 2D NMR data; 2 was thus named L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-L- rhodinose-β-rhodomycinone. C 65.8) in 1. Consistently,

Compound 3 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. It was found to have the same molecular formula as compound 2 (C38H48O15) on the basis of HRESIMS. These two compounds identical 1H and 13C NMR spectra. also exhibited almost Careful analysis of these data revealed a key diﬀerence in each trisaccharide linkage order between 2 and 3. The trisaccharide chain in 3 was found to be L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L- fucose. This diﬀers signiﬁcantly from the L-rhodinose-2-deoxy- L-fucose-L-rhodinose trisaccharide found in 2. This key diﬀerence in trisaccharides was made clear only after comprehensive interpretation of full sets of 2D NMR data, especially COSY and HMBC correlations (Figure 5) for each compound. On the basis of these results and conclusions compound 3 was subsequently named L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose- 2-deoxy-L-fucose-β-rhodomycinone. Compound 4 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder, and its molecular formula established as C38H48O14 on the basis of HRESIMS. Similarities observed for both the 1H and 13C NMR data for 4 and 3 indicated that both compounds contained the same trisaccharide. The only distinct spectroscopic diﬀerence between 3 and 4 involved the presence of two coupled doublet signals (δ H 3.26, J = 19.0 Hz) assigned as C-10-linked methylene protons in compound 4; this was in stark contrast to the previously noted C-10 methine of 3. Detailed analysis of the 2D NMR data (Figure 5) established the structure of 4 as L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose- 10-decarbomethoxy-ε-rhodomycinone.

Compound 5 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder, and its molecular formula established as C44H58O17 on the basis of HRESIMS. Notably, the ion peaks observed for this species revealed the clear presence of an additional C6H9O2 relative to the same data previously generated for trisaccharide 3. We reasoned that this may be attributable to an additional L- rhodinose moiety. Comparisons of 1H and 13C spectra for 5 versus compound 3 revealed the presence of four sugars in 5, although it was clear that they were contiguous and, thus, constituted a tetrasaccharide. Consistent with this logic, four anomeric carbons at δ C 101.4, 100.4, 100.3, and 99.6 were also observed. Thus, the tetrasaccharide chain consisting of four L- rhodinose moieties attached in a manner highly similar to that seen with 3 was noted. Also noteworthy was that this tetrasaccharide was found to be attached to the aglycone in a fashion similar to that noted with 3. On the basis of these data and their relationships to compounds 1−4 we ultimately named 5 as L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose-L-rhodinose-β-rhodo- mycinone.

Compound 6 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C38H48O16 on the basis of HRESIMS, which revealed that 6 contains one O atom more than compound 3. Comparisons of the 1H, 13C, and 2D NMR spectroscopic data for 6 with those of 3 (Table 1, Figure 5) revealed that 6 possesses an additional C-3″ OH substitution relative to 3; the methylene group at C-3″ (δ H 1.73, δ C 24.3) in 3 is replaced by an oxygen-bearing methine carbon (δ H 4.11, δ C 65.3) in 6. In short, sugar unit B (L-rhodinose) in 3 is hydroxylated to render 2-deoxy-L-fucose as the central sugar of the pendant trisaccharide in 6. This structural diﬀerence is consistent with changes observed for the neighboring C-4″ shift; in 3 the resonance for C-4″ is δ C 75.0, but in 6 the same resonance is signiﬁcantly deshielded to δ C 82.8. Consistently, HMBC correlations from H-1″ and H-4″ to C-3″ as well as the COSY correlation of H-2″/H-3″ conﬁrmed this substitution. have linkages of C-1′−C-6′, C-1″−C-6″, and C-1‴−C-6‴ with the aid of 1H−1H COSY correlations (Figure 5). Each sugar moiety was found to be linked through C-1‴−O−C-4″, C-1″− O−C-4′ on the basis of HMBC correlations from H-1‴ to C-4″ and H-1″ to C-4′ (also from H-4′ to C-1″ and H-4″ to C-1‴). Accordingly, the structure of compound 6 containing an L- rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-2-deoxy-L-fucose chain was eluci- dated. Compound 7 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder and formula as 6 was (C38H48O16). These two compounds also exhibited almost identical 1H and 13C NMR spectra, although careful data analysis revealed the two compounds to diﬀer by the ordering of sugar units. A full set of 2D NMR data, especially COSY and HMBC correlations (Figure 5), enabled us to comprehensively determine the precise nature of trisaccharide diﬀerences that characterize compounds 6 and 7. Keeping in mind that each trisaccharide contains two fucose moieties and one rhodinose group, it was found that the rhodinose group in 7 is ﬂanked with fucose moieties, whereas in 6 the rhodinose moiety is the terminal sugar. This is to say that 7 contains a pendant 2-deoxy- L-fucose-L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose chain, whereas the tri- saccharide chain of 6 is L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-2-deoxy- L-fucose. Thus, the structure of 7 was established and named 2- deoxy-L-fucose-L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-β-rhodomyci- none.

Compound 8 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder, and its molecular formula was established as C38H48O15 on the basis of HRESIMS. In a fashion similar to that observed when comparing structures 4 versus 3, compound 8 was found to diﬀer from 6 only with respect to C-10. Spectroscopic data for 6 and 8 were eﬀectively identical with the exception of resonances at δ H 2.57 and 3.25 in 8, consistent with methylene signals, which were absent for 6. Conversely, NMR data for 6 had clearly shown the presence of a C-10 OH moiety as well as a methine signal at δ H 4.86; both were absent in spectra of compound 8. Accordingly, it became clear that 8 is simply the C-10 deoxy congener of 6; given this and its relationship to rhodomycinones, we have named 8 as L-rhodinose-2-deoxy-L- fucose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-10-decarbomethoxy-ε-rhodomycinone. Compound 9 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C32H38O14 on the basis of HRESIMS. NMR experiments and comparison of the resulting data with those of 6 revealed the absence of one sugar moiety in 9 relative to 6. Only two anomeric methine resonances at δ H 5.48 and 4.97 were observed in the 1H NMR. 13C NMR data veriﬁed the presence of only two anomeric centers in 9. With these data in hand a disaccharide chain consisting of two 2- deoxy-L-fucose moieties was established; as with previously characterized anthracyclines 1−8, sugar tethering for 9 was found to involve the aglycone C-7 OH and C1′ sugar unit A. Accordingly, 9 was named 2-deoxy-L-fucose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-β- rhodomycinone.

Compound 10 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C38H48O17 on the basis of HRESIMS. Compound 10 was found to contain two O atoms more than compound 2 and only one more O atom than compound 6. This suggested the incorporation of three 2- deoxy-L-fucose sugar moieties within the usual trisaccharide chain; this hypothesis was validated following detailed 2D NMR analyses. Thus, 10 was identiﬁed as 2-deoxy-L-fucose-2- deoxy-L-fucose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-β-rhodomycinone. found to have the same molecular DOI: 10.1021/acs.jnatprod.8b00212 J. Nat. Prod. SCSIO 1666/17C4. Compound 11 was isolated as a red powder. Its molecular formula was established as C38H46O16 on the basis of HRESIMS. In comparing NMR data sets for 11 and compound 6, it was noted that the 13C NMR spectrum for 11 displayed a new resonance at δ C 209.9, suggestive of an additional carbonyl group. HMBC correlations from H-2‴, H-3‴, and H-6‴ to C- 4‴ made clear than the OH-bearing methine at C-4‴ in 6 is replaced in 11 with a carbonyl group. In short, the terminal L- rhodinose in 6 is replaced in 11 with its oxidized L-cinerulose variant. This new compound was named L-cinerulose-2-deoxy- L-fucose-2-deoxy-L-fucose-β-rhodomycinone.

Compound 12 was isolated as a red, amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C38H46O15 on the basis of HRESIMS. Like 11, the terminal sugar of 12 was found to be L- cinerulose, as determined on the basis of 13C NMR data and HMBC correlation analyses. Signiﬁcantly, the only diﬀerence between compounds 12 and 11 is that the ﬁrst sugar moiety (aglycone-linked) of the trisaccharide in 12 is L-rhodinose; the corresponding sugar in 11 is 2-deoxy-L-fucose. Thus, the structure of 12 was elucidated and named L-cinerulose-2-deoxy- L-fucose-L-rhodinose-β-rhodomycinone. Metabolites 1−15 and the cytorhodins appear to share from the similar biosynthetic origins and machineries the ε-rhodomycinone backbone. The only perspective of diﬀerence between the two systems is the sugar tailoring steps, in which both SlgG and CytG2 transfer the L-rhodinose (or 2-deoxy-L-fucose) unit to the C-7 position of the aglycone scaﬀold, ultimately furnishing the pendant polysaccharide moieties (Figure 4). The cyt gene cluster is expressed in the genetically modiﬁed strain Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/ΔtrdA1DH, in which tirandamycin production has been abolished; the cyt cluster appears to be only poorly expressed in the wild-type strain and may even be silent. In this study, gene insertions to divert metabolic ﬂux to the type II PKS pathway were carried out. Additionally, isolated from the anthracycline metabolites Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/ΔtrdA1DH and its mutant strains were found to feature L-rhodosamine tethered to either the C-7 or C-10 positions. Biosynthetically, these sugar moieties are

derived from dTDP-D-glucose, following a sequence of dehydration, ketoreduction, epimerization, and other tailoring steps. Interestingly, recombinant strain SCSIO 1666/17C4 yielded genetically engineered metabolites in which the ﬁrst sugar unit attached to C-7 of 1−13 was not an L-rhodosamine as generally anticipated. Cosmid p17C4 encodes for all requisite L-rhodinosyl biosynthetic machineries as well as the GT SlgG, a homologue of CytG2 (29% identity). One additional copy of the L-rhodinosyl biosynthetic genes and two homologous GTs for L-rhodinose may well inhibit the L- rhodosamine transfer process. As indicated, combinational biosynthetic approaches clearly hold a place in strategies to (i) expand the chemical space occupied by natural products and (ii) diversify these glycoside analogues. Cytotoxicity of Compounds 1−15. Anthracycline anti- biotics 1−15 displayed cytotoxicity against six human cell lines including melanocyte cancer cells MDA-MB-435, large cell lung cancer cells NCI-H460, highly metastatic breast cancer cells MDA-MB-231, colorectal cancer cells HCT-116, hepatocellular cells HepG2, and the noncancerous breast epithelial cell line MCF10A (IC50 values of 40.2−0.2 μM; Table 3). Compounds 4 and 13 displayed the greatest cytotoxic activity against HCT- 116 cells with IC50 values of 0.3 and 0.2 μM, respectively. It is noteworthy that compounds 4 and 8 were not active against MDA-MB-231, suggesting the importance of the O-bearing substituent at C-10 for this activity.

In conclusion, we have reported the isolation, character- ization, and cytotoxicity of 12 new and three known members of anthracycline antibiotics from a recombinant Streptomyces sp. SCSIO 1666/17C4 strain. Compounds 1−15 displayed a spectrum of cytotoxicity against a panel of human tumor cell lines. Notably, compounds 4 and 13 signiﬁcantly inhibited the growth of HCT-116 cells with IC50 values of 0.3 and 0.2 μM; notably, these data are highly similar to those obtained for the clinically important epirubicin, a positive control used in this study. The mutant strain SCSIO 1666/ 17C4 was placed onto modiﬁed ISP-4 agar plates and incubated at 28 °C. The mycelium was ﬁrst inoculated into each of the 250 mL Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 50 mL of MAM2ab medium (0.5% soybean ﬂour, 0.5% soluble starch, 0.2% yeast extract, 0.2% peptone, ·7H2O, 0.4% 2% glucose, 3% sea salt, 0.05% K2HPO4, 0.05% MgSO4 NaCl, 0.2% CaCO3, pH 7.2−7.4) and incubated at 28 °C on rotary shakers (200 rpm) for ∼36 h. Following 36 h of fermentation, each of the seed cultures was transferred to 1 L Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 200 mL of MAM2ab medium. Flasks were incubated at 28 °C on rotary shakers (200 rpm) for 7 d. A total of 15 L of fermentation culture was harvested and centrifuged (3600 rpm, 10 min). The supernatant was extracted with equal volumes of butanone three times, and the mycelium cake was repeatedly extracted with 2 L of acetone to yield crude extracts. The two organic fractions (butanone and acetone) were ultimately combined due to their similar HPLC metabolite proﬁles.

Isolation. The crude extract (10.5 g following solvent removal in vacuum) was subjected to silica gel column chromatography using −MeOH mixture (100/0, 99/1, 98/2, gradient elution with a CHCl3 96/4, 94/6, 92/8, 90/10, 80/20, 0/100, v/v) to give nine fractions (A1−A9), respectively. Fraction A3 was found to bear all the targeted anthracycline compounds. The following preparative HPLC (Welch Ultimate XB-C18, 21.2 × 250 mm, 10 mL/min) was employed to get the unpuriﬁed compounds 1−15. Further puriﬁcation was carried out by semipreparative HPLC (YMC-Pack ODS-A, 10 × 250 mm, 2.5 mL/min) using elution with CH3CN and 0.1% acetic acid in H2O. We ultimately obtained pure compounds 1 (8.5 mg, tR 21.2 min), 2 (3.0 mg, tR 18.3 min), 3 (4.5 mg, tR 17.8 min), 4 (3.2 mg, tR 22.1 min), 5 (3.1 mg, tR 19.7 min), 6 (2.8 mg, tR 14 min), 7 (1.8 mg, tR 14.5 min), and 8 (2.4 mg, tR 20.3 min), 9 (1.5 mg, tR 13.5 min), 10 (2.2 mg, tR 12.0 min), 11 (5.6 mg, tR 15.0 min), 12 (2.3 mg, tR 20.5 min), 13 (3.5 mg, tR 23.2 min), 14 (25.1 mg, tR 18.6 min), and 15 (30 mg, tR 16.1 min).
